org.logicmill.util.concurrent

Interface KeySource<T>

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    KeySet, RandomKeySet, RandomKeyStream

    public interface KeySource<T>
    An interface for classes that provide sets of keys for testing hash algorithms. An instance of any implementation will produce a finite number of keys. This allows tests to be written with the assumption that they can (in general) run until the key source is exhausted. A key source implementation may or may not know at construction time how many keys it will be able to provide. A programmer has the option of allowing the key source to allocate an individual buffer for each key, or to reduce garbage generation by passing the source a buffer in which to put a key. Key source implementations may provide a hint for for buffer allocation (see getKeySizeHint().
    Author:
    David Curtis

    • Method Detail

      • getKey

        T getKey()
        Returns the next available key. If no key is available, returns null.
        Returns:
        next available key, or null if none is available

      • hasMoreKeys

        boolean hasMoreKeys()
        Returns true if more keys are available from this source. In general, test programs using key sources should follow this pattern: 
        
 while (source.hasMoreKeys()) {
        byte[] key = source.getKey();
        //... use key ...
 }
        Returns:
        true if keys are available

      • getKeySizeHint

        int getKeySizeHint()
        Suggests a reasonable buffer allocation to accommodate keys from this source, for use with #getKey(byte[]).
        Returns:
        the maximum expected size of a key from this source

      • getKeyCount

        int getKeyCount()
        Returns the number of keys available from this source after construction or reset. If a source cannot reasonably determine this in advance, the return value is -1.
        Returns:
        number of keys available at initialization, or -1 if unknown

      • reset

        void reset()
        Resets the state of the source to the state that existed immediately after initialization. Precise meaning may vary among source implementations.
